<h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-900 mt-10 mb-4 tracking-tight">What Are the Legal Requirements to Get Married in Maryland?</h2>
<p class="text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Getting legally married in Maryland comes down to four things: both people need to be at least 18, you've got to appear together at a Maryland Circuit Court, you'll need a valid marriage license, and your ceremony must be performed by a registered or ordained officiant. One witness needs to be there too.</p>

<p class="font-semibold text-charcoal mb-2">Eligibility:</p>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 text-charcoal-muted mb-6">
  <li>Both applicants need to be 18 or older</li>
  <li>Neither of you can be currently married</li>
  <li>No Maryland residency required. Out-of-state and international couples are fully eligible.</li>
  <li>First-cousin marriages aren't permitted in Maryland</li>
</ul>

<p class="font-semibold text-charcoal mb-2">Documents required at the Circuit Court:</p>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 text-charcoal-muted mb-6">
  <li>Valid photo ID for both of you (driver's license, passport, or state ID)</li>
  <li>Social Security numbers for both applicants</li>
  <li>A certified divorce decree or death certificate if either of you was previously married (photocopies aren't accepted)</li>
  <li>Both of you must show up at the same time. No exceptions.</li>
</ul>

<p class="font-semibold text-charcoal mb-2">Recognized officiant types:</p>
<ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1 text-charcoal-muted mb-8">
  <li>Judges and magistrates</li>
  <li>Justices of the Peace</li>
  <li>Licensed religious ministers or clergy</li>
  <li>Online-ordained ministers. Universal Life Church ordinations are valid in Maryland.</li>
</ul>

<h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-900 mt-10 mb-4 tracking-tight">How Do You Apply for a Maryland Marriage License? Step by Step</h2>
<p class="text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed mb-6">Getting a Maryland marriage license takes under an hour at most Circuit Courts. Most counties hand it to you the same day.</p>

