<h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-900 mt-10 mb-4 tracking-tight">Can a Friend Legally Officiate a Wedding in Maryland?</h2>
<p class="text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Yes. Maryland accepts online ordinations through recognized organizations. Universal Life Church (get-ordained.com) is the most commonly used and is explicitly recognized in Maryland. The process takes about 5 minutes online and is free. Your friend doesn't need to apply for a state license or register with any county office. They just need to be listed on the marriage license as the officiant and sign it at the ceremony.</p>
<p class="text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong class="text-charcoal">What your friend will need to do:</strong></p>
<ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2 text-charcoal-muted mb-6">
  <li>Complete the online ordination through ULC or a similar recognized organization</li>
  <li>Be listed as the officiant when you apply for your Maryland marriage license</li>
  <li>Prepare and deliver the ceremony script (typically 15 to 30 minutes)</li>
  <li>Sign the marriage license immediately after the ceremony</li>
  <li>Ensure the signed license gets returned to the Circuit Court within 60 days</li>
</ol>
<p class="text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed mb-8">The preparation requirement is where friend officiants sometimes struggle. Writing and delivering a wedding ceremony isn't something most people have done before. They'll need 4 to 8 weeks to prepare, and ideally a full rehearsal run-through. Many couples discover too close to the date that their friend's more anxious about it than they let on earlier, and there's no time left to course-correct.</p>

