<h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-900 mt-10 mb-4 tracking-tight">What Questions Should You Ask a Baltimore Wedding DJ Before Booking?</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-4 text-charcoal-muted mb-8">
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">"How many weddings have you DJed in Baltimore, and can I see some recent playlists or setlists?"</strong> Baltimore's venues have different acoustic environments. An experienced Baltimore wedding DJ knows how sound behaves at Clipper Mill vs. The Engineers Club vs. an outdoor park setting.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">"What's your process for music planning and do-not-play lists?"</strong> You need a specific answer here, not a vague "we'll talk closer to the date." Good wedding DJs have a structured planning process that runs 4 to 8 weeks before the event.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">"What backup equipment do you bring?"</strong> A professional answer: redundant hard drives, backup laptop or controller, secondary speaker setup for emergencies. If they can't name their backup equipment specifically, that's a signal.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">"Have you worked at our venue before?"</strong> Venue familiarity matters for setup logistics, load-in timing, and how they handle the acoustics. It's not required, but worth asking.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">"What's included in your price : MCing, lighting, setup and breakdown time?"</strong> Two DJs quoting $1,500 can have very different deliverables. Clarify whether ceremony sound, cocktail hour, lighting, and overtime rates are included or add-ons.</li>
</ol>

