<h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-900 mt-10 mb-4 tracking-tight">What Should You Ask a Baltimore Venue Before You Sign?</h2>
<p class="text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Most couples tour a venue, love what they see, and sign before asking the questions that determine whether it actually fits their budget. Here's what matters most.</p>

<ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-4 text-charcoal-muted mb-8">
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">What's the catering policy and the minimum spend?</strong> In-house catering venues often require $5,000 to $15,000 in food and beverage minimums on top of the venue fee. That $4,000 venue rental can become $12,000 in total venue costs before you've booked a single outside vendor.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">What's included and what's extra?</strong> Tables, chairs, linens, parking staff, AV equipment, and cleanup fees are often separate. Always ask for the total cost, not just the venue rental line item.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">What's the noise curfew?</strong> Many Baltimore venues require music off by 10pm or 11pm. If you're planning a late reception, confirm this before you fall in love with the space.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">What's the weather contingency?</strong> If there's no indoor backup for outdoor ceremonies, you're budgeting $1,500 to $4,000 for a tent rental as weather insurance. Maryland weather is unpredictable in spring and fall.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">Is the event exclusive-use?</strong> Some venues book multiple events in a day. Ask explicitly whether you'll have the full space exclusively during your event window.</li>
</ol>

