  {
    slug: 'wedding-caterers-baltimore',
    title: 'Best Wedding Caterers in Baltimore, Maryland (2026)',
    description: "Baltimore wedding caterers with real pricing, food styles, and what to ask before signing. From a planner who's coordinated catering at 50+ Maryland weddings.",
    category: 'Vendor Guides',
    readTime: '9 min read',
    relatedService: { label: 'John helps negotiate catering contracts', href: '/services/full-service-wedding-planning', cta: 'Full-Service Planning' },
    content: `
<p class="text-lg sm:text-xl text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed mb-6">Catering is typically 25 to 35% of a Maryland wedding budget. It's the biggest single vendor cost for most couples, and it's the one that's most likely to have surprise charges buried in the contract. Getting the catering decision right matters more than almost any other vendor choice.</p>

<p class="text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed mb-8">I've reviewed catering contracts and coordinated with caterers across 50+ Maryland weddings. Here's what actually determines whether catering goes well, what the pricing looks like in 2026, and what questions you'll want answered before you sign anything.</p>

<h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-900 mt-10 mb-4 tracking-tight">How Much Does Wedding Catering Cost in Baltimore?</h2>
<p class="text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Baltimore wedding catering costs $40 to $150+ per person depending on service style, menu quality, and what's included. Here's how the tiers break down for 2026.</p>

<div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
  <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
    <thead>
      <tr class="bg-rose-50">
        <th class="text-left p-3 font-display font-semibold text-stone-900 border border-rose-light/40">Service style</th>
        <th class="text-left p-3 font-display font-semibold text-stone-900 border border-rose-light/40">Per person cost</th>
        <th class="text-left p-3 font-display font-semibold text-stone-900 border border-rose-light/40">What's typically included</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody class="text-charcoal-muted font-body">
      <tr><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30 font-medium text-charcoal">Food trucks / casual</td><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30">$25 to $45</td><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30">Food only, no service staff</td></tr>
      <tr class="bg-cream"><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30 font-medium text-charcoal">Buffet catering</td><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30">$40 to $65</td><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30">Food + basic service staff</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30 font-medium text-charcoal">Stations / family style</td><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30">$55 to $85</td><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30">Food + service + setup</td></tr>
      <tr class="bg-cream"><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30 font-medium text-charcoal">Plated dinner service</td><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30">$75 to $120</td><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30">Full service staff, plated courses</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30 font-medium text-charcoal">Premium plated</td><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30">$100 to $150+</td><td class="p-3 border border-rose-light/30">Chef-driven menu, full staff, premium ingredients</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>

<p class="text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed mb-8">These per-person costs don't always include alcohol, bar service staff, rentals (linens, china, glassware), gratuity, or the setup and breakdown fees. A quote that looks like $65 per person can become $90 per person after all the add-ons. Always request a fully itemized quote before comparing caterers.</p>

<h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-900 mt-10 mb-4 tracking-tight">What Types of Wedding Catering Work Best in Baltimore?</h2>
<p class="text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed mb-6">The right service style depends on your venue, guest count, and the feel you want for the reception.</p>

<div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
  ${[
    { style: 'Buffet', best: "Guest counts over 75, budget-conscious couples, casual or semi-formal receptions", desc: "The most common service style at Baltimore mid-range weddings. Guests serve themselves from stations. Lower per-person cost than plated. Works well at most venues. Downside: the buffet line takes time and can create gaps in conversation flow." },
    { style: 'Family Style', best: "Intimate weddings under 100, couples who want a communal feel", desc: "Shared platters placed at each table. Creates a warm, family dinner atmosphere. Slightly higher cost than buffet but more distinctive. Works particularly well at Baltimore's smaller historic venues and industrial spaces." },
    { style: 'Plated Dinner', best: "Formal receptions, venues with full-service infrastructure", desc: "Each guest receives a served individual plate. Creates the most formal atmosphere and the smoothest guest experience. Highest per-person cost. Requires more service staff and typically more catering coordination on the day." },
    { style: 'Food Stations / Interactive', best: "Younger couples, creative venues, casual receptions", desc: "Multiple themed stations (charcuterie, carving station, pasta bar, etc.) that guests rotate between during cocktail hour or reception. Very popular at Baltimore's industrial and arts venues. High guest engagement. Variable per-person cost." },
    { style: 'Food Trucks', best: "Micro-weddings, backyard receptions, very casual events under 75 guests", desc: "One or two food trucks for the reception. Works best for genuinely casual events where the food is part of the vibe. Lower cost but limited menu customization and no service staff included." },
