  `).join('')}
</div>

<h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-900 mt-10 mb-4 tracking-tight">What Hidden Costs Should You Watch for in Baltimore Catering Contracts?</h2>
<p class="text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">This is where most catering budget surprises happen. I've reviewed dozens of Baltimore catering contracts, and these are the items that consistently add 15 to 30% to the initial quote.</p>

<ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-4 text-charcoal-muted mb-8">
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">Service charges and gratuity.</strong> Many caterers add a mandatory 18 to 22% service charge on top of the per-person food cost. This is separate from any additional tip you might leave. On a $6,000 catering bill, an 18% service charge adds $1,080 before you've touched the bar.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">Rentals.</strong> China, glassware, linens, serving equipment, and chafing dishes are often not included in the per-person quote. Ask specifically what's included and get a separate rental quote if anything's missing.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">Bar service.</strong> Alcohol itself is usually priced separately from food catering. Beer, wine, and spirits packages run $20 to $50+ per person depending on what you're serving. A full open bar for 4 hours for 75 guests adds $1,500 to $3,500 to the catering total.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">Staffing ratios.</strong> Some caterers quote based on a minimal staff ratio and charge extra for additional service staff. For plated dinners, you typically need 1 server per 10 to 15 guests. Confirm the staffing plan is included in the quote.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">Setup and breakdown fees.</strong> Many caterers charge separately for venue setup and end-of-night breakdown. This can run $300 to $800 depending on the venue and complexity.</li>
</ol>

<h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-900 mt-10 mb-4 tracking-tight">What Questions Should You Ask a Baltimore Wedding Caterer?</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-4 text-charcoal-muted mb-8">
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">"Is this a fully itemized quote, and what's not included?"</strong> This should be the first question before evaluating any catering proposal. You need to compare total costs, not per-person food costs.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">"What's your policy on outside alcohol and who provides the bar service?"</strong> Some Baltimore caterers allow you to provide your own alcohol and just charge for bar staff. Others require you to purchase through them at significantly higher margins.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">"Have you catered at our venue before?"</strong> Venue familiarity affects kitchen setup, timing, and how smoothly service runs. Not essential, but worth knowing.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">"What's your tasting process and when does it happen?"</strong> Most professional caterers offer a tasting before the final menu is locked. If a caterer doesn't offer this, that's a signal worth noting.</li>
  <li><strong class="text-charcoal">"What's your backup plan if a key staff member is sick on the wedding day?"</strong> A professional catering company should have a clear staffing backup process. Individual caterers sometimes don't.</li>
</ol>

<div class="bg-cream border border-rose-light/40 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
  <p class="font-display font-semibold text-charcoal mb-2">Catering contract negotiation</p>
  <p class="text-sm text-charcoal-muted font-body mb-4">John reviews catering contracts as part of his full-service and partial planning packages. He's caught mandatory minimums, exclusivity clauses, and hidden fees in catering contracts that would have cost clients $500 to $2,000 over their expectations. It's one of the highest-value parts of working with a planner at the budget level.</p>
  <a href="/services/full-service-wedding-planning" class="btn-primary text-sm">See Full-Service Planning</a>
</div>

<h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-charcoal mt-10 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions About Baltimore Wedding Catering</h2>

<details class="bg-white border border-rose-light/40 rounded-lg mb-3" open>
  <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-5 cursor-pointer">
    <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-charcoal">How much does wedding catering cost for 75 guests in Baltimore?</h3>
  </summary>
  <div class="px-5 pb-5">
    <p class="text-sm text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed">For 75 guests with buffet-style service, budget $3,500 to $5,500 for food and basic service. Add $1,500 to $2,500 for beer, wine, and a basic bar. Total catering cost for 75 guests in Baltimore typically runs $5,000 to $8,000 for mid-range service, before gratuity and rental add-ons. Plated dinner service adds $1,500 to $3,000 to that range.</p>
  </div>
</details>

<details class="bg-white border border-rose-light/40 rounded-lg mb-3">
  <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-5 cursor-pointer">
    <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-charcoal">Can you use outside catering at Baltimore wedding venues?</h3>
  </summary>
  <div class="px-5 pb-5">
    <p class="text-sm text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed">It depends entirely on the venue. Some Baltimore venues (Clipper Mill, Cylburn Arboretum, Motor House, most parks) allow outside catering through an approved vendor list. Hotel ballrooms and some historic venues require in-house catering with mandatory minimums. Always confirm the catering policy before booking a venue, since it's the biggest variable in total catering cost.</p>
  </div>
</details>

<details class="bg-white border border-rose-light/40 rounded-lg mb-8">
  <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-5 cursor-pointer">
    <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-charcoal">When should you book a Baltimore wedding caterer?</h3>
  </summary>
  <div class="px-5 pb-5">
    <p class="text-sm text-stone-600 font-light leading-relaxed">For peak season Saturdays, 9 to 12 months in advance for established Baltimore caterers. Less in-demand caterers and weekday dates have more flexibility at 4 to 6 months out. Book catering before you finalize your guest count, since the catering proposal will lock you into a per-person structure that's harder to revise significantly after signing.</p>
  </div>
</details>

<p class="text-xs text-charcoal-muted font-body">John coordinates catering logistics and reviews catering contracts for Maryland weddings. If you're comparing quotes and not sure what to look for, the free consultation is a useful starting point.</p>`,
